class Solution {
    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        List<Integer>[] g = new ArrayList[values.length];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        g[0].add(-1);
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for (int v : values) {
            ans += v;
        }
        return Math.max(dfs(0, -1, g, values), ans);
    }
    private long dfs(int x, int fa, List<Integer>[] g, int[] values) {
        if (g[x].size() == 1) {
            return values[x];
        }
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x, g, values);
            }
        }
        return Math.min(values[x], loss);
    }
}
In this code, we first create the adjacency list representation of the tree using the given edges. Then, we calculate the sum of all values which will be our initial maximum score. We then traverse the tree starting from the root node, for each node, we calculate the minimum loss we can get from its children if we set the current node's value to 0. We update our maximum score by taking the maximum of the current score and the minimum loss plus the current node's value.

