Lastly, ((x >> 1) & x) is checking if all substrings of length 2 in x contain at least one '1'. If x = 000 or 001 or 011, then x >> 1 & x = 000. So it means all substrings contain at least one '1'. If x is something like 110, then x >> 1 & x = 100 which is not 000, so there is a substring with no '1'.

